ce:section.ce:para:
The as-fabricated active substrate is used as a SERS substrate for organic molecule sensing, and R6G is chosen as a model probe molecule. Also, to investigate the role of GQDs, and rough surface provided by SiO2 microspheres, the SERS spectra of Si, Ag/Si, Ag-GQDs/Si, Ag/SiO2/Si were detected in the experiment for comparison. As shown in Fig. 4
                     , the observed SERS signals from those substrates located at 614, 772, 932, 1198, 1279, 1358, 1507 and 1647 cm−1 are consistent well with the previous reports on Raman spectra of R6G [35,36]. But the signal intensity of the Ag-GQDs/SiO2/Si substrate is noticeably the strongest one. Compared with the signal intensity of Ag/Si substrate (its surface morphology is shown in Fig. S4), the Raman enhancement factors (EFs) for the Ag-GQDs/SiO2/Si substrate is 14.6 by using the signal intensity of band position at 1279 cm−1 (Table 1
                     ). From the different enhancement effects of Ag-GQDs/Si and Ag/SiO2/Si substrates, it is believed that the synergistic effects of GQDs and SiO2 template endow the Ag-GQDs/SiO2/Si substrate excellent SERS performance. Furthermore, we studied the SERS enhancement mechanism of Ag-GQDs/SiO2/Si substrate as discussed below. From the EEM aspect, the gap-induced localized plasmon coupling between the adjacent Ag NPs provided by GQDs is responsible for highly active SERS effect. GQDs with a tiny size ranged from 1 to 4 nm, can locate at the inter particle gaps between Ag NPs as reflected from the HRTEM image (Fig. 2). These gaps of 1–4 nm are suitable for working as Raman “hot spots” with a view to the LSPR effect which plays a critical role in EEM enhancement. Therefore, for the Ag-GQDs/SiO2/Si substrate, it is equivalent to introduce a high density of “hot spots” in Ag substrate and then resulted in highly enhanced Raman signal. Meanwhile, from the CEM aspect, the enhancement effect is related to the contact degree between substrate and interested molecules [37]. GQDs have π–π layer structure in nature, resulting in more closer contact with R6G molecules through π–π stacking for one hand. On the other hand, although many oxygen functional groups on the surface of GQDs consumed in the formation of Ag-GQDs compounds, but part of them still retained in the surface of Ag-GQDs compounds. Those groups result in their electronegativity (zeta potential = −5.58 mV) [25] and good hydrophilic [38] of GQDs, and endow them improved adsorption ability of R6G molecules through electrostatic interactions, because R6G molecules have electropositivity. The above two effective enhancement factors of R6G molecules adsorption will both facilitate the charge transfer between Ag-GQDs compounds and R6G molecules and guide the R6G molecules precisely to the “hot spot” sites, resulting in a higher SERS signal than Ag NPs alone. The improved charge transfer behavior between Ag-GQDs compounds and R6G molecules can be supported by the observed charge transfer between other graphene and graphene derivatives and probe molecules [27,35,37]. In addition, the subtle rough surface of the Ag-GQDs/SiO2/Si substrate benefiting from the SiO2 template also provides a larger surface area and further guarantees the effective adsorption of R6G molecules, as well as favors the capture of the incident light for SERS. Thus, both the GQDs and SiO2 template contribute to higher SERS signals.
